Ammarella Inc (AMBA.O) Price Target
Strengthens our thesis Impact to our thesis
Meaningful upside Financial results versus consensus
Meaningful revision higher Direction of next 12- month consensus EPS
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research

Delivered another strong quarter from Edge Al strength. While waiting for autonomous automotive enthusiasm to resume, edge based Al in other applications is emerging as the clear near- term growth driver. Notable Al momentum in portable video, drones, and enterprise infrastructure markets.

Q2 revenue of \(\) 95.5M\(exceeded guidance, up 11\% q/q and 50\% y/y\) FY26 revenue growth expectations raised to 31 - 35\%, midpoint implies - \(\) 379M\$ . Automotive remains a priority, but emphasizing non auto prospects Edge Al and loT drive near- term growth; autos remain a long- term opportunity, though seeing less activity right now. Price target raised from \(\) 80\(to\) \ \(96\) due to strong Edge Al prospects.

Numbers remain strong in the near term, with visibility starting to build into 2H. Ambarella is executing well and benefiting from the rising breadth of edge Al applications. Q2 revenue of \(\) 95.5M\(came in above the high end of guidance, up 11\% q/q and nearly 50\% y/y. Momentum continues to be driven by loT and Edge Al, where portable video and robotics are providing fresh legs of growth. Auto grew mid- single digits, but to \(\) 76\(renew in the mid- teens and represented >75\% of revenue. Management raised\) \ \(26\) revenue growth expectations to 31- 35% (vs. prior 19- 25%), with the midpoint implying - \(\) 379M\$ - - an all- time high.

A quarter ago, management had guided conservatively for 2H, but they are now seeing strong order book as well as higher expectations for both units and prices this year. Management reports no evidence of unusual inventory builds in distributor or customer channels.

AMBA is seeing extremely strong demand for edge Al. Portable video (e.g., Insta360), robotics (including aerial drones ramping in late FY26), and emerging edge infrastructure (N1 SoC win for edge infrastructure) are now contributing to their bullish outlook. These markets are diversifying in AMBA's loT portfolio beyond traditional security. Management highlighted that non- security loT - portable video, drones, robotics - is outgrowing security, with portable video the fastest

In autos, AMBA is actively bidding on OEM projects with their advanced CV3 family. However, design cycles remain long and decisions infrequent. As management reiterated, we expect loT to continue to outgrow automotive in the near term. That said, we continue to see high value in their technology. AMBA's wins with some of the most important tier one automotive companies in the ADAS space (Continental and Bosch) clearly show the capability. It's frustrating that hasn't turned to OEM wins for the most important sockets, but that mostly reflects a lack of automotive innovation outside of China or Tesla (covered by Adam Jonas). The company will continue to invest in CV3, but meanwhile the growth engine is the faster- cycle, broader edge AI opportunities.

Details on the July quarter: Revenue of \(\) 95.5m\(up\) 11.2\% \(q/q and\) 49.9\% \(y/y) was ahead of the street and our estimate of\) \ \(90m\) . Non- GAAP gross margin of \(60.5\%\) (down 150bps \(q/q and 279bps y/y) was 59bps below the street at\) 61.1\% \(and 82bps below our estimate of\) 61.3\% \(. EPS of\) \ \(0.15\) was above the street and our estimate of \(\) 0.05\$

For the October quarter: Revenue was guided to \(\) 104\(mn at the midpoint (up 8.9\% q/q and 25.8\% y/y), above the street at\) \ \(91.1m\) and our estimate of \(\) 92.3m\(. Gross margin was guided to\) 60.8\% \(at the midpoint (up 25bps q/q and down 181bps y/y), below the street at\) 61.0\% \(and our estimate of\) 61.3\%\$

Changes to estimates: We model October revenues/non- GAAP GM/non- GAAP EPS of \(\) 104.1m/60.8\%/\(\) 0.18\$ . Our FY26 revenue, non- GAAP gross margin and non- GAAP EPS estimates go from \(\) 349.6m/61.5\%/\(\) 0.12\(to\) \ \(380.6m/61.0\%/\) \ \(0.47\) . For FY27 we model revenue, non- GAAP gross margin, and non- GAAP EPS at \(\) 410.3m/60.7\%/\(\) 0.48\(vs. our prior\) \ \(390.9m/59.8\%/\) \ \(0.55\)

Thoughts on the stock: Stay Ow, as the strength of the company's core Edge AI technology is starting to turn to revenue. The importance of Ambarella technology - AI inference at the edge with low power - is going up, and we continue to be impressed by their technology. AMBA is benefiting from an loT product cycle with CV5/CV7, and our hope is that this will handoff to other pipeline elements moving forward. While it's not our primary thesis, we do believe that the strategic value of the company to a larger company more able to turn the company's vision leadership into revenue remains higher than the current market cap (see our previous note here please note that the company has not commented on the report and we are not aware of potential transactions). We see the potential for their long- term autos story; in the meantime, edge AI diversification is proving the more powerful near- term growth driver. We raise our PT from \(\) 80\(to\) \ \(96\) , and increase our multiple from 8x to 9x CY2026 sales of \(\) 410\(mn given strong AI growth drivers, to take high end of the peer range.
Long term prospects with CV3 are exciting but L2+ autonomy development is slow.

We like Ambarella's fundamental position and think that bears generally underestimate the company's technology leadership. We think that the company's computer vision (CV) products are unique and expect CV to drive transformative growth

Home security and automotive applications will add growth on top of existing core market growth (core markets include surveillance, dash mounted autos and OEM auto surround view/digital rear view mirrors)
Sensor fusion beginning with radar and camera begins to materialize, though we do not yet base material revenue growth on this market
Source: Refinitiv, Morgan Stanley Research

CV products take auto market share, consumer grows more than expected, and sensor fusion business materializes
CV solution begins to overcome auto incumbents; further relationships with tier one suppliers, surveillance growth continues
- Design win momentum accelerates, including some in sensor fusion products, and later robotics
- Core business grows more meaningfully, as adoption of CV drives strong growth across all segments
Incremental growth in security camera opportunities combines with a burgeoning automotive segment
- Increasing CV penetration leads to improved ASPs and larger SAM
- Current pace of EV and AV adoption drives automotive revenue
- Design win momentum continues
Automotive revenue takes longer than expected to ramp; Security camera growth stalls
- AMBA design wins and market share gains in the automotive segment result in smaller revenue opportunities than expected, leading to slower growth and lower multiple
- CV penetration rate decelerates in security camera market
- Computer vision products fail to make any real impact beyond initial surveillance wins.
